## 3. GraphQL Error Handling

### 3.1 Parsing GraphQL Errors

**Utility:** `src/shared/errors/parseGraphQLError.ts`

```typescript
import { CombinedError } from 'urql'

export function parseGraphQLError(error: CombinedError | undefined): string {
  if (!error) return 'An unknown error occurred'

  // Network error (no internet, server unreachable)
  if (error.networkError) {
    return 'Unable to connect. Please check your internet connection.'
  }

  // GraphQL errors (backend returned errors)
  if (error.graphQLErrors.length > 0) {
    const firstError = error.graphQLErrors[0]

    // Check for user-friendly message from backend
    const userMessage = firstError.extensions?.userMessage as string | undefined
    if (userMessage) {
      return userMessage
    }

    // Map error codes to user messages
    const code = firstError.extensions?.code as string | undefined
    switch (code) {
      case 'UNAUTHENTICATED':
        return 'Your session has expired. Please log in again.'
      case 'FORBIDDEN':
        return 'You do not have permission to perform this action.'
      case 'NOT_FOUND':
        return 'The requested resource was not found.'
      case 'VALIDATION_ERROR':
        return firstError.message // Backend provides user-friendly validation messages
      case 'ALREADY_EXISTS':
        return 'This record already exists.'
      default:
        // Log unexpected error codes
        console.error('[GraphQL Error]:', code, firstError.message)
        return 'Something went wrong. Please try again.'
    }
  }

  // Fallback
  return 'Something went wrong. Please try again.'
}
```

**Usage:**
```typescript
const [result] = useSubmitRsvpMutation()

if (result.error) {
  const errorMessage = parseGraphQLError(result.error)
  showToast(errorMessage)
}
```

---

### 3.3 Backend-Boundary 429 Routing (WAF / CDN / Reverse Proxy)

When AWS WAF, CloudFront, or any reverse proxy rejects a request at the edge, the response's **Content-Type** — not the 429 status — determines where URQL routes it in `CombinedError`:

| Response shape | URQL routes to |
|---|---|
| `text/plain` body (or any unparseable body) | `error.networkError` with `.status === 429` |
| `application/json` body shaped `{"errors":[{...,"extensions":{"code":"RATE_LIMITED"}}]}` | `error.graphQLErrors[0]` (NOT `networkError`) |

**Rule:** Any parser that handles rate-limit errors (especially for localization) MUST check BOTH branches symmetrically:

```typescript
// Inside parseGraphQLError / parseGraphQLErrorLocalized:

// Branch 1 — text/plain or unparseable WAF response
if (error.networkError && (error.networkError as any).status === 429) {
  return t('error.rate_limited')
}

// Branch 2 — JSON-bodied WAF response (most common in production)
if (error.graphQLErrors.length > 0) {
  const firstError = error.graphQLErrors[0]
  if (firstError.extensions?.code === 'RATE_LIMITED') {
    return t('error.rate_limited')
  }
  // ... rest of graphQLErrors handling
}
```

**Why this matters:** Handling only `networkError.status` silently leaks the WAF's English string to users in non-English locales — the parser falls through to `firstError.message` which is the WAF's hardcoded English text. This was the iter-3 → iter-4 incident on the login-i18n feature (June 2026).

**Reference fixture:** `e2e/web/captcha-waf-429.spec.ts` documents the real AWS WAF 429 JSON-body shape. Mirror it exactly when writing tests — never invent a synthetic shape (see `04_frontend-testing-strategy.mdc` §6.5).

**Mirror the fix in parallel helpers.** If the codebase has both `parseGraphQLError` (no-`t`) and `parseGraphQLErrorLocalized` (with-`t`), fix BOTH branches in BOTH helpers symmetrically and pin the equivalence with a drift-guard test (see `04_frontend-testing-strategy.mdc` §3.1 "Drift-guard tests for parallel helper pairs").

---

### 3.4 Extracting Field-Specific Errors

**Backend pattern (GraphQL extensions):**
```json
{
  "errors": [
    {
      "message": "Validation failed",
      "extensions": {
        "code": "VALIDATION_ERROR",
        "fieldErrors": {
          "email": "Email is required",
          "password": "Password must be at least 8 characters"
        }
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

**Frontend parser:**
```typescript
export function extractFieldErrors(error: CombinedError | undefined): Record<string, string> {
  if (!error?.graphQLErrors) return {}

  const firstError = error.graphQLErrors[0]
  const fieldErrors = firstError.extensions?.fieldErrors as Record<string, string> | undefined

  return fieldErrors ?? {}
}
```

**Usage in forms:**
```tsx
const [result, submitRsvp] = useSubmitRsvpMutation()

const fieldErrors = extractFieldErrors(result.error)

<TextInput
  value={email}
  onChangeText={setEmail}
  error={fieldErrors.email}
/>
```

